[[File:Sa·πÉsƒÅra.jpg|thumb|Symbolic depiction of Sa·πÉsƒÅra]]
{{Jainism}}
'''''Sa·πÉsƒÅra''''' ('''transmigration''') in [[Jain philosophy]], refers to the worldly life characterized by continuous rebirths and [[reincarnation]]s in various realms of existence. {{IAST|[[Sa·πÉsƒÅra]]}} is described as mundane existence, full of suffering and misery and hence is considered undesirable and worth [[renunciation]]. The ''Sa·πÉsƒÅra'' is without any beginning and the [[Jƒ´va (Jainism)|soul]] finds itself in bondage with its [[Karma in Jainism|karma]] since the beginning-less time. ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|Moksha]]'' is the only way to be liberated from ''sa·πÉsƒÅra''.

== Influx of karmas (''asrava'')==
According to the Jain text, [[Tattvartha sutra]]:{{quote|(There are two kinds of influx, namely) that of persons with passions, which extends transmigration, and that of persons free from passions, which prevents or shortens it.|''TattvƒÅrths≈´tra'' (6-4-81){{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2011|p=81}}}}

Activities that lead to the influx of karmas (''[[asrava]]'') which extends transmigration are:{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2011|p=81-82}}
*Five senses
*Four passions (''[[Kashaya (Jainism)|kasƒÅya]]'')
**Anger
**Ego
**Deceit
**Greed
*The non-observance of the five vows
*Non-observance of the twenty-five activities like Righteousness 

;''Sa·πÉsƒÅra bhavanƒÅ''

Jain texts prescribe meditation on twelve forms of reflection (''bhƒÅvanƒÅ'') for those who wish to stop the above described ''asrava''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1917|p=52}} One such reflection is ''Sa·πÉsƒÅra bhavanƒÅ''.
It has been described in one of the Jain text, ''[[SarvƒÅrthasiddhi]]'' as:{{quote|Transmigration is the attainment of another birth by the self owing to the ripening of karmas. The five kinds of whirling round have been described already. He, who wanders in the endless cycle of births and deaths, undergoing millions of afflictions in innumerable wombs and families, takes different relationships such as father, brother, son, grandson, etc, or mother, sister, wife, daughter and so on, being propelled by the mechanism of karmas. The master becomes servant and the servant master, just as an actor acts several parts on the stage. To be brief, sometimes one becomes one‚Äôs own son. There is no end to the transformations undergone by the self owing to the influence of karmas. Thus to reflect on the nature of mundane existence is contemplation on worldly existence. He who contemplates thus is alarmed at the miseries of transmigration and becomes disgusted with worldly existence. And he who is disgusted with it endeavours to free himself from it.{{sfn|S.A. Jain|1992|p=246}}}}

[[Champat Rai Jain]], a 20th century Jain writer in his book ''The Practical Dharma'' wrote:
{{cquote|Endless is the cycle of transmigration; painful is every form of life; there is no happiness in any of the four conditions of existence; devas, human beings, animals and residents of hells are all involved in pain and misery of some kind or other; moksha alone is blissful and free from pain; the wise should, therefore, only aspire for moksha; all other conditions are temporary and painful."{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1917|p=52}}}}

